   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_936_1829_01_00_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1829-01-31">Jany <unclear>31</unclear> 1829</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>My dear Miss Edgeworth</persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               - I have<lb/>
               just returned <choice>
                  <orig>fm</orig>
                  <reg>from</reg>
               </choice>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#STK">Scotland</placeName> where<lb/>
               I heard the news of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">your sister's</persName>
               <lb/>
               marriage - an event on which<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockS1">my wife</persName> begs leave to join her<lb/>
               congratulations <choice>
                  <orig>w</orig>
                  <reg>with</reg>
               </choice> mine. I hope<lb/>
               the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Lady</persName> will permit us to<lb/>
               make her acquaintance as I<lb/>
               understand she is to be settled<lb/>
               in this vicinity.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I saw at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Abbotsford-House_STK">Abbotsford</placeName> your<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">youngest brother</persName> who was then<lb/>
               visiting the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrewX1">Brewsters</persName> - I don't<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_936_1829_01_00_page02.jpg"/>
               know where your brother <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName>
               <lb/>
               is but have a message for<lb/>
               him which perhaps you will be<lb/>
               kind enough to forward -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I transcribe a note drawn<lb/>
               up by a reverend friend of<lb/>
               mine new here who takes <del/>
               <lb/>
               charge of the Scientific department<lb/>
               of "the Family <unclear>Litany</unclear>" - a<lb/>
               miscellany about to be <choice>
                  <orig>
                     <unclear>pub<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
                     </unclear>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>published</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MurrJ1">Mr Murray</persName> (&amp; of which<lb/>
               I enclose a prospectus)<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_936_1829_01_00_page03.jpg"/>
               "I want a popular account<lb/>
               of the rise &amp; present state of<lb/>
               civil engineering in this<lb/>
               country &amp; it ocurs to me that<lb/>
               all the information which<lb/>
               need be given on the subject<lb/>
               might be embodied in a<lb/>
               series of biographies of such<lb/>
               men as <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ2">Brindley</persName>, <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SmeaJ1">Smeaton</persName>,<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RennJ1">Rennie</persName> &amp;c &amp;c &amp;c. If <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">Mr<lb/>
               Edgeworth's</persName> avocations<lb/>
               &amp; inclinations permit him<lb/>
               to draw up such a book<lb/>
               perhaps he <choice>
                  <orig>w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>would</reg>
               </choice> take the<lb/>
               trouble to calculate the<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_936_1829_01_00_page04.jpg"/>
               extent to which he thinks it<lb/>
               <choice>
                  <orig>w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>would</reg>
               </choice> run - &amp; then, I doubt not,<lb/>
               we <choice>
                  <orig>shd</orig>
                  <reg>should</reg>
               </choice> be able to offer him<lb/>
               ample remuneration for his<lb/>
               services."<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Perhaps this sort of business<lb/>
               is wholly out of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>yr</orig>
                     <reg>your</reg>
                  </choice> brother's</persName>
               <lb/>
               way; but I happened accidentally<lb/>
               to mention his name &amp; since<lb/>
               this has come of it, it can<lb/>
               do little harm to submit the<lb/>
               proposal. It is possible, if<lb/>
               he be not <hi rend="underline">very</hi> busy, that<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_936_1829_01_00_page05.jpg"/>
               he may not dislike such an<lb/>
               exertion - at all events <hi rend="underline">you</hi>
               <lb/>
               will excuse me for having<lb/>
               thought so.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I left <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">Sir Walter</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotA1">Anne Scott</persName>
               <lb/>
               in the best of health and<lb/>
               spirits. He has a <title ref="./Workography.xml#AnneG1">Novel</title>
               <lb/>
               nearly ready of which I<lb/>
               read &amp; was delighted with<lb/>
               the first volume - all<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#SZ">Swiss</placeName> scenery &amp; the Burgundian<lb/>
               period -<lb/>
               I hope you don't cry a halt<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_936_1829_01_00_page06.jpg"/>
               in <hi rend="underline">Taking for Granted.</hi>
               <lb/>
               <note>Though Lockhart refers to the novel as "Taking for Granted," Sir Walter Scott named the novel "Anne of Geierstein."</note>
            </p>
            <closer>
               Believe me ever, dear<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss Edgeworth</persName>, your<lb/>
               very faithful servant<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockJ1">
                  <hi rend="underline">J G Lockhart</hi>
               </persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>
                  PS &amp; NB. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PhilH1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Philpotts</persName>
                  <lb/>
                  has turned a stout <choice>
                     <orig>pro-<lb/>
                  catholic</orig>
                     <reg>pro-Catholic</reg>
                  </choice>
                  <lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
         </div>
